if($^O eq'MSWin32')
	{
	$usage_command="unitas.exe -input path/to/sequence.file -species genus_species";
	}
else
	{
	$usage_command="./unitas -input path/to/sequence.file -species genus_species";
	}

########## USAGE ##########
$usage="

                                                           X
                                                          oXX.o
                                                         .XXXX
                                                        .XXXXX
                                                       .XXXXX.
                                                      .XXXXXXXXXo
                                                     oXXXXXX' 'XXX.
            XXX                                   .oXXXXXXXX. .XXXXo
           XXXXX.  .oXXXXoo..                 ...oXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX
            XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXo'''
               XXXXXXXXXXXXXXX------------------XXXXXXXXXXXX'
           .X.   'XXXXXXXXXXXX      unitas      XXXXXXXXXXXXX
         XXXXXXooXXXXXXXXXXXXX------------------XXXXXXXXXXXXXoooooo...XXXX
       .XXXX'XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX'''XXXXXXXXXXXXXXX''
    .oXXXX'    ''XXXXXXXXXXX' 'XXXXXXXXXXXXXXX'''''        '''       ''
   oXXXX'          'XXXXX''
   XXXX'


 Version: ..... $unitas_version
 Date: ........ $last_modified


                              ### Usage ###
 All you need to start is a file that contains your sequence data in FASTQ,
 FASTA, SAM or ELAND3 format and a connection to the internet. Start the unitas
 Perl script from the command line (terminal) using the following command:

    perl unitas.pl -input path/to/sequence.file -species genus_species

 When you run the standalone executable file use this command instead:

    $usage_command

 unitas uses ncRNA (and cDNA) sequences from Ensembl and thus supports species
 included in the latest Ensembl release. Use the option -supp_spec to display a
 list of all supported species/strains. If you want to annotate sRNA sequences
 from a different species chose a closely related species or use the option
 -species like this:

    -species x

 In the latter case you must provide your own reference sequence file(s) using
 the option

    -refseq sequence_1.fas [-refseq sequence_2.fas ...]

 Use the option -show_options to display a list with all available command line
 options.


                          ### How to cite unitas ###
